{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501353","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501353"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:28:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:28:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1752"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1752","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1752"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.51,0.21,0.12,0.12,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1752"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50243"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1752","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1752"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1752"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35503"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"910"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11513"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13995"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27137"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42388"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46318"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50243","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/50243"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman presents to the ED with a 2-hour history of central chest discomfort. She has a past medical history of hypertension, hypercholesterolaemia and myocardial infarction (2 years ago), which was treated with a stent. While in hospital for her myocardial infarction, second-degree AV block (Mobitz II) was noted on her ECG, and a permanent pacemaker was inserted. Her medications include aspirin 100mg, atorvastatin 40mg and ramipril 2.5mg.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. On auscultation, heart sounds are dual with no murmur and the lungs are clear bilaterally. Vital signs include BP 156/94.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA 12-lead ECG (25mm/s) is performed in the emergency department, which shows the following in lead II:\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Based on the symptoms and ECG provided in the stem, which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Normal dual chamber pacemaker rhythm","Ischaemic changes","Left bundle branch block changes","Normal atrial pacemaker rhythm","ECG artifact"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ECG demonstrates \u003Cstrong\u003Enormal dual chamber pacemaker rhythm \u003C/strong\u003E(A-V sequential pacing), and pacing spikes are shown before the p wave (e.g. atrial pacing) and before the QRS complex (e.g. ventricular pacing). In this ECG there is both 100% atrial capture and 100% ventricular capture, as P waves follow each atrial pacing spike, and a QRS complex follows each ventricular pacing spike. However, ECGs of people with dual chamber pacemakers may show a pacing strike only before the p wave, or QRS complex, or before both. While not applicable in this case, it is important to note that an absence of pacing spikes and associated pacing complexes doesn\u0027t always equate to pacemaker failure, as there may be adequate native conduction. Of note, this ECG morphology is typical of the ventricular lead in the RV apex, as opposed to septal, his-bundle, or bi-ventricular pacing which will have a different QRS morphology (depending on the site lead insertion).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Enormal atrial pacemaker rhythm \u003C/strong\u003Ewould show pacing spikes only before p waves, and not before QRS complexes as in the ECG provided, the latter of which indicate ventricular pacing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis lead does show ST elevation, however it is not in keeping with \u003Cstrong\u003Eischaemic changes\u003C/strong\u003E. Firstly, a diagnosis of an acute myocardial infarction (AMI) typically requires ST elevation in two or more contiguous leads (e.g. both leads II and III). In a paced ventricular rhythm (similar to a left bundle branch block (LBBB)), the ST segments and T waves should be discordant to the majority of QRS complexes. In the ECG provided, the QRS complexes are negative, and thus ST segment and T wave elevation is normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003ESgarbossa\u0027s criteria \u003C/em\u003Eis used to identify AMI in the presence of a LBBB. The criteria includes:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EConcordant ST elevation \u0026gt;1mm in leads with a positive QRS complex\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EConcordant ST depression \u0026gt;1 mm in V1-V3\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EProportionally\u003C/em\u003E excessive discordant STE in \u2265 1 lead anywhere with \u22651 mm STE, as defined by \u226525% of the depth of the preceding S-wave\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELeft epicardial pacing results in a QRS morphology that resembles right bundle branch block (RBBB). Conversely, right ventricle pacing results in a QRS morphology similar to \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft bundle branch block \u003C/strong\u003E(LBBB). Ventricular pacing results in a broad QRS complex (\u0026gt;120ms), as the left ventricle receives the depolarising impulse from the right ventricle, as also occurs in LBBB. However, given the clear pacing spikes preceding both the p wave and QRS complex, it is most likely that the broad QRS complexes are a result of pacemaker activity, and not a true LBBB.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EECG artifact \u003C/strong\u003Ecan manifest in various ways, including a variable baseline and distorted waves, present across all leads. However, the ECG demonstrates clear and repetitive atrial and ventricular spikes, followed by p waves and QRS complexes, respectively. Thus, it is unlikely to be artifact, as these ECG changes can be attributed to a dual chamber pacemaker rhythm.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dual chamber pacemaker rhythm typically shows pacing spikes before the p wave and before the QRS complex","Ventricular pacing rhythms have a similar appearance to left bundle branch block"],"references":["Life in the Fast Line. Sgarbossa Criteria [Internet]. 2021 Mar 19. Available from: https://litfl.com/sgarbossa-criteria-ecg-library/","ECG \u0026 Echo Learning. Interpretation of Pacemaker ECG [Internet]. Section 1, Chapter 5. Available from: https://ecgwaves.com/topic/ecg-pacemaker-rhythm-malfunction-failure-tachyarrhythmia/#:~:text=The%20cardinal%20manifestation%20of%20pacing,if%20both%20chambers%20are%20paced."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35503"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1752"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"624"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"624","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/624"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/372fbeca-e2b8-482e-a3f3-c55808fadb17.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/372fbeca-e2b8-482e-a3f3-c55808fadb17.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":782,"height":196}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35503","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/35503"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-09T11:08:15+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-09T13:48:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1752"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50243"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}}